+Herr Staiacci Foley (filmmaking)

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia






A Foley artist at workFoley is the reproduction of everyday sound 
effects that are added to film, video, and other media 
in post-production to enhance audio quality.[1]These reproduced sounds can 
be anything from the swishing of clothing and footsteps to squeaky doors 
and breaking glass. The best Foley art is so well integrated into 
a film that it goes unnoticed by the audience.[2] It helps to create a 
sense of reality within a scene. Without these crucialbackground noises, 
movies feel unnaturally quiet and uncomfortable.Foley artists recreate the 
realistic ambient sounds that the film portrays. The props and sets of a 
film often do not react the same way acoustically as their real life 
counterparts.[2] Foley sounds are used to enhance the auditory experience 
of the movie. Foley can also be used to cover up unwanted sounds captured 
on the set of a movie during filming, such as overflying airplanes or 
passing traffic.[2]The term "Foley" is also used to describe a place, such 
as Foley-stage or Foley-studio, where the Foley process takes place.
+Herr Staiacci James Faul-Ei
